verdict.refinedSolution:
Preferred (tenet-aligned, per FW-1/FW-2): delete the entire rsc package. It is a mechanical port of React Server Components helpers (createAI/useUIState/getMutableAIState/streamUI...) that has no place in a KMP transport library; callers should use Flow<T> directly, which gives update->emit, completion, and error->Flow-exception for free. This subsumes FW-4 entirely. ABI: removing an @ExperimentalAiSdkApi surface is permitted.

If the surface must survive a release, do NOT swap MutableSharedFlow for a bare Channel (it breaks the replay=64 multi-subscriber fan-out). Instead make the stream's element type carry the terminal signal as data (T1: sealed class, T5: exhaustive — no out-of-band throw):

@ExperimentalAiSdkApi
public sealed class StreamableValueEvent<out T> {
    public data class Update<T>(val value: T) : StreamableValueEvent<T>()
    public data class Error(val throwable: Throwable) : StreamableValueEvent<Nothing>()
    public data object Done : StreamableValueEvent<Nothing>()
}

The controller emits these into the existing MutableSharedFlow<StreamableValueEvent<T>>; error() becomes `updates.emit(StreamableValueEvent.Error(throwable))` (mirroring StreamableUIController, which already emits an Error part — make the two consistent). readStreamableValue can then either expose Flow<StreamableValueEvent<T>> (let callers `when`-match, never lose Done/Error) or map to Flow<T> that re-throws on Error and completes on Done. This preserves replay/fan-out, makes the error observable by collectors, and removes the throw-in-producer footgun. Add a test asserting `readStreamableValue(value).collect{}` (or its event form) observes the error. Mark all of it @ExperimentalAiSdkApi so the signature change is allowed.

