verdict.refinedSolution:
Sealify, don't flatten. Replace the two `data class`es with a sealed-class hierarchy that keeps the approval invariant and unifies the helpers:

BEFORE: `data class ToolUI(...approvalId, signature...)` + `data class DynamicToolUI(...)` + outputAs/inputAs + dynamicOutputAs/dynamicInputAs (4 fns).

AFTER:
```
@Serializable
public sealed class ToolUI(
    public val toolCallId: String,
    public val toolName: String,
    public val state: ToolCallState,   // becomes sealed State once SEAL-01 lands
    public val input: JsonElement? = null,
    public val output: JsonElement? = null,
    public val error: String? = null,
    public val preliminary: Boolean = false,
    public val providerMetadata: Map<String, JsonElement>? = null,
) : UIMessagePart {
    @Serializable public data class Static(
        ...base args...,
        val approvalId: String? = null,
        val signature: String? = null,
    ) : ToolUI(...)
    @Serializable public data class Dynamic(...base args...) : ToolUI(...)
}
```
Then ONE pair of helpers on the base:
```
public fun <T> outputAs(part: ToolUI, s: KSerializer<T>): T? =
    if (part.state != ToolCallState.OutputAvailable) null else part.output?.decodeAs(s)
public fun <T> inputAs(part: ToolUI, s: KSerializer<T>): T? =
    if (part.state == ToolCallState.InputStreaming) null else part.input?.decodeAs(s)
```
deleting dynamicOutputAs/dynamicInputAs. Renderers branch `when (part) { is ToolUI.Static -> ...; is ToolUI.Dynamic -> fallbackCard(part) }` — exhaustive, type-driven (T1), and approvalId/signature stay unrepresentable on Dynamic (T5).

This is one ABI break, not a half-measure: do it in the SAME PR as SEAL-01 so ToolCallState→sealed State and the type unification rebaseline api/torad-aisdk.klib.api + api/jvm/torad-aisdk.api once. Because the merge changes the existing public `ToolUI` from a concrete data class to a sealed class (no longer constructible directly, no copy()), @Deprecated migration is awkward — prefer a clean break gated to the next minor with a CHANGELOG note and a migration snippet (`ToolUI(...)` → `ToolUI.Static(...)`, `DynamicToolUI(...)` → `ToolUI.Dynamic(...)`).

If SEAL-01 slips: still land the cheap independent win now — extract a shared supertype/interface exposing state/input/output so the two dynamic* helpers collapse into the static pair, eliminating the verbatim duplication without touching the type fork or breaking constructor ABI.

Do NOT ship the `dynamic: Boolean` / `kind` variant from the original finding — it trades a type fork for a flag and silently widens the approval state space.

Model each variant's data-shape as a sealed CLASS (T1, Marcos's explicit preference) so exactly one form is present, mirroring the existing UIMessagePart SourceUrl/SourceDocument split.

For File/Image — extract a shared nested sealed class. Because ContentPart variants are @Serializable polymorphic with @SerialName, the nested Data must be its own closed polymorphic hierarchy:

  @Serializable
  public sealed class FileData {
      @Serializable @SerialName("inline") public data class Inline(val base64: String) : FileData()
      @Serializable @SerialName("remote") public data class Remote(val url: String) : FileData()
  }
  @Serializable @SerialName("file")
  public data class File(val mediaType: String, val data: FileData, val filename: String? = null, val providerMetadata: Map<String, JsonElement>? = null) : ContentPart
  // Image: same, reuse FileData.

For Source — split by the enum it already carries into proper subclasses, exactly matching UIMessagePart:

  @Serializable public sealed class Source : ContentPart {
      @Serializable @SerialName("source-url") public data class Url(val url: String, val title: String? = null, val providerMetadata: Map<String, JsonElement>? = null) : Source()
      @Serializable @SerialName("source-document") public data class Document(val mediaType: String, val title: String, val filename: String? = null, val providerMetadata: Map<String, JsonElement>? = null) : Source()
  }

This deletes the sourceType enum entirely (the @SerialName discriminator now carries that information — T3 pre-computed decision via the type tag, not a runtime enum the caller must branch on).

ABI/wire migration (CONTEXT mandates additive + @Deprecated over silent breakage): this is unavoidably a binary AND wire break (base64/url getters vanish, JSON shape changes), so a clean additive path is not fully possible. Soften it: (a) keep deprecated computed-property shims `val base64: String? get() = (data as? Inline)?.base64` and `val url: String? get() = (data as? Remote)?.url` plus a @Deprecated secondary constructor accepting the old (mediaType, base64, url) tuple that maps to the sealed form — this preserves SOURCE compat for one release even though binary getters change signature; (b) bump the documented wire version and provide a deserialization migration since old payloads carry flat base64/url/sourceType rather than a discriminated child. Regenerate api/jvm/torad-aisdk.api and api/torad-aisdk.klib.api in the same change. Per the truncation note, ride StreamEvent.SourcePart (Streaming.kt:118) along in the same PR since it shares the identical enum+nullable union, keeping the domain and stream sides consistent with the already-correct UI side.

