Introduce transparent serializable value classes and use them everywhere these ids flow:

BEFORE:
```kotlin
public data class ToolResult(val toolCallId: String, val toolName: String, val output: JsonElement, ...)
```
AFTER:
```kotlin
@JvmInline @Serializable public value class ToolCallId(public val value: String) {
    init { require(value.isNotBlank()) { "ToolCallId must not be blank." } }
    override fun toString(): String = value
}
@JvmInline @Serializable public value class ToolName(public val value: String) {
    init { require(value.isNotBlank()) { "ToolName must not be blank." } }
    override fun toString(): String = value
}
public data class ToolResult(val toolCallId: ToolCallId, val toolName: ToolName, val output: JsonElement, ...)
```
`@Serializable` on a `@JvmInline value class` serializes transparently to the underlying JSON string, so the v6 wire shape (T2) is byte-identical — only the Kotlin type changes. `approvalId` becomes its own `ApprovalId` value class so it can never be passed where a `ToolCallId` is expected. Follow the convention already established in ModelRef.kt for ProviderId/ModelId.

verdict.refinedSolution:
Introduce three transparent serializable value classes and thread them through every id site in one ABI-breaking pass (ModelMessage, Streaming/StreamEvent, ui/UIMessage, Tool, ToolLoopAgent + factories):

```kotlin
@JvmInline @Serializable public value class ToolCallId(public val value: String) {
    init { require(value.isNotBlank()) { "ToolCallId must not be blank." } }
    override fun toString(): String = value
}
@JvmInline @Serializable public value class ToolName(public val value: String) {
    init { require(value.isNotBlank()) { "ToolName must not be blank." } }
    override fun toString(): String = value
}
@JvmInline @Serializable public value class ApprovalId(public val value: String) {
    init { require(value.isNotBlank()) { "ApprovalId must not be blank." } }
    override fun toString(): String = value
}
```

Key points beyond the original:
1. Add @Serializable EXPLICITLY (ModelRef's existing value classes are NOT @Serializable because they never cross the wire — do not blindly "follow the convention" there). A @Serializable @JvmInline value class wrapping one String serializes to a bare JSON string, so ToolResult/ToolCall/etc. emit identical v6 JSON. Lock this with a round-trip test asserting Json.encodeToString(ToolResult(ToolCallId("c1"), ToolName("search"), ...)) still contains "toolCallId":"c1" as a bare string (and decode back).
2. Also convert ToolExecutionContext.toolCallId (Tool.kt:1097) to ToolCallId — it is in the finding's surface and tools self-identifying for telemetry benefit from the same guard.
3. ABI: regenerate BOTH api/jvm/torad-aisdk.api and api/torad-aisdk.klib.api via apiDump; expect mangled JVM getters (e.g. getToolCallId-<hash>). This is a breaking change for a published explicitApi library — gate behind a minor/major bump; a @Deprecated additive shim is impractical here because the field types themselves change, so document it as a deliberate break in the changelog rather than attempting silent migration.
4. Do ToolCallId + ToolName + ApprovalId together (they co-occur in the same constructors) to avoid a half-migrated state where some sites are typed and some are raw.
5. Separately (follow-up, not this finding): the approvalId: String? = null "null defaults to toolCallId" semantics is a T5 null-means-two-things smell; once ApprovalId exists, consider whether absence should be modeled explicitly rather than reusing the tool-call id.

