verdict.refinedSolution:
Keep the wire bag as the transport at the boundary, but eliminate the stringly-typed read-back by giving each PROVIDER module its own typed accessor — do not enumerate providers in a core sealed class.

1. Core stays decoupled. Optionally wrap the transport in a value class to make intent explicit without ABI churn beyond the type swap:
   @JvmInline public value class ProviderMetadata(public val raw: Map<String, JsonElement>) {
       public fun <T> decode(provider: String, serializer: KSerializer<T>): T? = raw[provider]?.decodeAs(serializer)
   }
   decodeProviderMetadata stays as the enabling primitive (it is NOT a band-aid).

2. Provider-owned typed read-back lives in the provider slice (T8). In the anthropic module:
   @Serializable public data class AnthropicMetadata(val cacheCreationInputTokens: Int? = null, val cacheReadInputTokens: Int? = null, val citations: List<Citation> = emptyList())
   public fun GenerateTextResult<*>.anthropicMetadata(): AnthropicMetadata? = providerMetadata.decodeProviderMetadata("anthropic")
   This gives callers fully typed access (T3 satisfied) while core never depends on Anthropic's schema.

